<output>
<analysis>
<has-cmf>The provided post does not contain a CMF number.  While the absence of a CMF number doesn't automatically exclude it from being considered electoral propaganda, it suggests it might not be directly linked to an officially registered campaign.</has-cmf>
<refers-to-candidate>The post's text is entirely in an unintelligible script, seemingly random characters.  Therefore, it does not refer to any specific parliamentary candidate.  Article 36 (7) - a does not apply.</refers-to-candidate>
<addresses-the-wide-population>Given that this is a paid Facebook post, it is inherently designed to reach a wide audience. The post's targeting parameters (insights) show a broad reach across various age groups and locations in Romania.  Therefore, it addresses the wide population.</addresses-the-wide-population>
<electoral-objective>Because the text is unintelligible, it's impossible to determine if the post has an electoral objective.  There is no discernible message promoting or discouraging votes for any candidate or party.  Article 36 (7) - c cannot be applied.</electoral-objective>
<journalism>The unintelligible nature of the text prevents assessment of whether it constitutes journalism or an attempt to influence voters. The images show a man speaking at a podium, which could be interpreted as a public speech, but without context, it's impossible to determine its purpose.</journalism>
<personal_opinion>The content is not expressing a personal opinion; it's nonsensical.  Therefore, it cannot be classified as a personal opinion not intended to influence the vote.</personal_opinion>
</analysis>

<conclusion>
<post_id>588550683761248</post_id>
<electoral-propaganda-analysis>
The post contains unintelligible text, making it impossible to determine if it constitutes electoral propaganda. The images alone are insufficient to establish an electoral objective or violation of Article 98 t).  While the post is categorized as "POLITICAL" and targeted towards a Romanian audience, the lack of comprehensible content prevents a definitive conclusion.  The absence of a CMF number further weakens the case for it being electoral propaganda.
</electoral-propaganda-analysis>
<electoral-propaganda-decision>FALSE</electoral-propaganda-decision>

<responsible-party-or-group>INDEPENDENT</responsible-party-or-group>

</conclusion>
